@startuml physics_system

package "Systems Layer" {
    class PhysicsSystem {
        + PhysicsSystem()
        + update(entities: std::vector<Entity*>, dt: float): void
        - applyGravity(entity: Entity*, dt: float): void
        - capVelocity(entity: Entity*): void
        - applyFriction(entity: Entity*, dt: float): void
        - integratePosition(entity: Entity*, dt: float): void
    }
    
    note right of PhysicsSystem::update
      Executes at a strict 60Hz (dt = 0.0167s).
      1. Apply Gravity (if not grounded)
      2. Cap max fall speed
      3. Apply grounded friction
      4. Position += Velocity * dt
      5. Set grounded = false (CollisionSystem resets this)
    end note
}

package "Domain Layer" {
    abstract class Entity {
        + position : Vector2D
        + velocity : Vector2D
        + active : bool
        
        ' Physics-specific attributes 
        ' (Often extracted into a PhysicsComponent in pure ECS)
        + grounded : bool
        + gravity_scale : float
    }
}

package "Infrastructure Layer" {
    class Constants <<Static>> {
        + static constexpr float GRAVITY
        + static constexpr float MAX_FALL_SPEED
        + static constexpr float FRICTION
        + static constexpr float FIXED_DT
    }
}

' Relationships
PhysicsSystem ..> Entity : <<iterates and mutates>>
PhysicsSystem ..> Constants : <<reads physical limits>>

@enduml

Key Architectural Takeaways
Stateless Processor: The PhysicsSystem itself holds very little state. 
It doesn't "own" the entities; it receives a reference/pointer to 
the active entity list, processes their data, and finishes its 
job for that frame.

Mutation over Encapsulation: In performance-critical game loops, 
systems often need direct access to public data 
members (like position and velocity on the Entity). 
Routing these updates through getters and setters millions 
of times per second can introduce unnecessary overhead, 
which is why they are exposed directly to the system.

The "Grounded" Handshake: Notice that Step 5 of the Physics 
logic explicitly sets entity.grounded = false. 
The Physics System always assumes an entity is 
falling until the CollisionSystem runs in the 
immediately following step. If the Collision 
System detects a floor, it sets grounded = true. 
This prevents the PhysicsSystem from endlessly 
accumulating gravity while Mario is standing still.
